label.value: MSL complex

definition.value: A histone acetyltransferase complex that catalyzes the acetylation of a histone H4 lysine residue at position 16. In human, it contains the catalytic subunit MOF, and MSL1, MSL2 and MSL3.

label.value: host cell mitochondrial intermembrane space

definition.value: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the host cell mitochondrial envelope.

label.value: host cell endosome lumen

definition.value: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the host cell endosome.

label.value: host multivesicular body

definition.value: A late endosome in which regions of the limiting host cell endosomal membrane invaginate to form internal vesicles -  host membrane proteins that enter the internal vesicles are sequestered from the host cytoplasm.

label.value: host cell Cajal body

definition.value: A class of nuclear body in the eukaryotic host cell, first seen after silver staining by Ramon y Cajal in 1903, enriched in small nuclear ribonucleoproteins, and certain general RNA polymerase II transcription factors -  ultrastructurally, they appear as a tangle of coiled, electron-dense threads roughly 0.5 micrometers in diameter -  involved in aspects of snRNP biogenesis -  the protein coilin serves as a marker for Cajal bodies. Some argue that Cajal bodies are the sites for preassembly of transcriptosomes, unitary particles involved in transcription and processing of RNA. The host is the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

label.value: Pup transferase activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of Pup from one protein to another via the reaction X-Pup + Y ---gt- Y-Pup + X, where both X-Pup and Y-Pup are covalent linkages.

label.value: divalent inorganic cation transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of inorganic cations with a valency of two from one side of the membrane to the other. Inorganic cations are atoms or small molecules with a positive charge that do not contain carbon in covalent linkage.
